zW.text:
If you want to use Stamp Font Engine in your projects, backpack the sprite named "Stamp Font" and drag it into any projects you want to use it in.

Credit is not hard to give and would be greatly appreciated! Putting something similar to "Text Engine by @-Rex-" in the Notes and Credits of your project would be sufficient.

zX.text:
Note: All blocks starting with "INTERNAL" are necessary for Stamp Font Engine to function, but are not meant to be used directly. You should simply leave them as they are and ignore them.
Default Values: Many inputs can be left blank, in which case a default value will be chosen. This has been done to make development easier and quicker.
Typography terms: "baseline" refers to the bottom of a line of text, as measured by the bottom of the letter H; "capline" refers to the top of a line of text, as measured by the top of the letter H.

zY.text:
This block changes which font is currently in use. Currently, the following built-in fonts are included:

- Source Sans Pro
- Source Sans Pro Bold
- Source Sans Pro Italic
- Open Sans

More fonts can be added by using the font injector linked to in the Notes and Credits.

zZ.text:
This block draws a single line of text to the canvas.

Options:
- Pos: The (x, y) position of the text on the screen
- Size: The height of the line, in pixels (the width is also scaled proportionally) (Default value: 16.0)
- Spacing: Extra spacing added between characters (referred to as Character Spacing), as measured in units roughly equal to the average width of a character (Default value: 0.0)
- Align: The position of the text relative to Pos
  - Horizontal Alignment (first input): Can be 'l', 'c', 'r' (without quotes), or a number.
     If a number is chosen, the value of the input is multiplied by the length of the line to determine the offset of the first character, which is added to the x-position.
     Letter to number conversion:
     - l (left) = 0.0
     - c (center) = -0.5
     - r (right) = -1.0
     (Default value: 'l' or 0.0)
  - Vertical Alignment (second input): Can be 'b', 'c', or 't' (without quotes), or a number.
     If a number is chosen, the value of the input is multiplied by Size to determine the offset of the baseline, which is added to the y-position
     Letter to number conversion:
     - b (bottom) = 0.0
     - c (center) = -0.5
     - t (top) = -1.0
     (Default value: 'b' or 0.0)
- Angle: The angle the text is rotated by, applied after Pos and Align. The center of rotation is Pos. Angles start at 0 degrees to the right and increase counterclockwise. (Default value: 0.0)
- Text: The text to be drawn

z!.text:
This block draws a multiple lines of text to the canvas.

Options:
- Pos: Same as above
- Size: Same as above
- Length: The maximum line length allowed, in pixels (Default value: 460.0)
- Bounds: The upper and lower y-levels before rotation, beyond which lines will not be rendered (Default values: Infinity, -Infinity)
- Spacing: Spacing between characters and lines
  - Character Spacing (first input): Same as above
  - Line Spacing (second input): Multiplies the spacing between lines. The value of the input is multiplied by 0.7 * Size to get the vertical spacing between lines. (Default value: 1.0)
- Align: The position of the text relative to Pos
  - Horizontal Alignment (first input): Same as above; calculated separately for each line
  - Vertical Alignment (second input): Can be 'b', 'c', or 't' (without quotes), or a number.
     If a number is chosen, the text moves upward by (value of input) lines. When set to 0.0, the imaginary baseline above the first line has the same y-position as Pos.
     Letter values:
     - t (top): The capline of the first line has the same y-position as Pos.
     - c (center): The entire body of text, from the capline of the first line to the baseline of the last line, is vertically centered on the y-position of Pos.
     - b (bottom): The baseline of the last line has the same y-position as Pos.
     (Default value: 1.0)
- Angle: Same as above
- Text: Same as above

z#.text:
Changes the "_y" variable to simulate moving down a certain number of empty lines.

Options:
- Number: The number of lines to move down "_y" by (Default value: 1.0)
- Size: Same as above
- Spacing: Same as Line Spacing above
- Angle: Same as above

Note: After using Print or WW Print, the "_x" and "_y" variables will be set to the position after the last letter. Vertical alignment will be taken into account when using Print, but only a Vertical Alignment of 't' will affect these values when using WW Print. For all other alignments when using WW Print, the alignment will be treated as if it were 1.0.

z%.text: If you want to better understand how any of these blocks or inputs work, some basic examples can be found in the "Main" sprite.

aRF8osu+N!a_7!|m?kbi: This is a text engine that draws text by stamping. Previously, stamp text engines had many disadvantages compared to pen text engines. However, with the release of Scratch 3.0 and this new stamp text engine, many of these disadvantages have been eliminated. Additionally, the use of stamping brings new features and advantages, such as support for effects and better text quality.

aRF8osu+N!a_7!|m?kbi: With previous stamp text engines, adding new fonts was tedious and generally not done by the users of such engines. Stamp Font Engine changes this by allowing almost any font to be injected into the Scratch project by using an external Javascript program. This process is quick, happens almost entirely automatically, and supports almost all .ttf and .otf font files.

aRF8osu+N!a_7!|m?kbi: Many previous stamp text engines have had issues with inconsistent spacing between characters due to using approximate numbers for character widths. Since Stamp Font Engine uses character width data calculated directly from the font file, this issue has been greatly mitigated, making text look much nicer and creating parity with pen text engines, which have typically not been affected by this issue.
